Household Clean Fuel Reliance by Region

##  Attaching packages  tidyverse 1.3.2

## Joining, by = c("Region", "Country", "Year", "Area_Type")

This chart shows the average percentage reliance on clean fuel sources in households across different world regions in the form of a bar chart. Of course, this is limited by the number of countries that WHO has this information on. From this chart, we can see that clean fuels are most prevalent in households in Europe and the Americas (which includes Caribbean countries). This prevalence is much decreased in Africa, which only has about a 25% average reliance. Using this in conjunction with the following map can help viewers compare the regions with worst air particle concentration with their use of clean fuels.

PM2.5 Concentrations Worldwide

This map visually illustrates the concentration of certain particulates in ambient air around the world. The more red a country is, the higher the concentration, ie. the more air pollution they suffer. From the visualization, it is clear that Asia, the Middle East, and North Africa have many countries with high particulate levels. Its interesting when comparing this to the previous chart, that Africa and Southeast Asia have low clean fuel reliance on average, whereas the Eastern Mediterranean region sees more clean fuel usage. There may be a correlation in the first two regions between low clean fuel reliance and poor air quality, but there is likely a different reason for the air pollution in Eastern Mediterranean.

Reliance on Clean Fuels and Air Pollution-Related Deaths

## Joining, by = c("Region", "Country", "Year")
## Joining, by = c("Region", "Country", "Year")
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula 'y ~ x'

This scatterplot shows each countrys average reliance on clean household fuels and the death rate per 100,000 due to air-pollution related causes. The use of a trend line helps show how strong of a relationship there is between these two variables. There seems to be little relationship between the two when the clean fuel usage is between around 0 and 70%. After this point, the line begins to curve down, indicating a negative relationship between the two; as reliance on clean fuels increases, the deaths related to air pollution decrease.
